INSERT INTO places VALUES(613,'bk_magazine','https://bk.asia-city.com/restaurants/restaurant-reviews/rongklanuea','<article>Rongklanuea</article>','2025-09-08 13:35:50.766509',13.7380744999999993,100.50762929999998984,'937 939 Song Wat Rd, Khwaeng Samphanthawong, Khet Samphanthawong, Krung Thep Maha Nakhon 10100, Thailand','ChIJd6ADLcOZ4jARi3zHoEpvWI8','https://maps.google.com/?cid=ChIJd6ADLcOZ4jARi3zHoEpvWI8','Rongklanuea','Restaurant','A crumbling two-storey shophouse tucked away on a quiet Songwat street has found a second life as an indie braised beef spot, Rongklannuea, winning hipsters'' hearts through its hearty bowls of fatty meat. Inside the ground-floor a massive giant pot filled with luscious cuts of beef greets you with its rich, herby notes—something makes your wait even more unbearable. Few seats and tables are available, and at some point the place might get so crowded that lines extend across the street. Insider tip: go after  area, the prices aren’t cheap, but the quality speaks for itself. On our visit we tried the Emperor braised beef noodle (B250), the most lavish option on offer featuring a medley of braised beef, beef balls, sliced tenderloins, tendons, and beef tongues—all topped with sweet chili oil and crisp garlic. It’s simplicity itself: the beef was soft but not dissolving while the savory sweet sauce on the top keeps you yearning for more. Add the patongo dough (B20) to wipe up the soup or let them soak up while indulging. Too much? There’s the regular beef noodle (B95) with added toppings for B60 each or rice with chicken gravy sauce (B100).','A cozy shophouse on a quiet street serves hearty bowls of braised beef that have captured the attention of food lovers. With limited seating, the atmosphere buzzes with excitement as patrons line up for dishes like the Emperor braised beef noodle. Rich flavors and quality ingredients make each bowl a satisfying experience worth the wait.','braised beef,indie restaurant,noodles',NULL,'{"openNow": f